body:
#### Summary
SoftAssertions output errors including a stack trace element for each error message.
```The following assertion failed:
1) [error-message]
at [stack-trace-element]
2) [error-message]
at [stack-trace-element]
```
With assertj soft assertions this works great and the stack-trace-element allows to jumb directly into at the assertion call in the test class.
However when using a custom class soft assertions and this class is declared in a non assertj package e.g. "org.example.project.assertions" the stack-trace-element is from the ByteBuddy proxied assertion class.
So the output is something like
```
at MyProjectClassAssert$ByteBuddy$zSZUiQrB$auxiliary$7Qx1CRh1.call(MyProjectClassAssert$ByteBuddy$zSZUiQrB$auxiliary$7Qx1CRh1.java:-1)
```

#### Example

With the following assertion classes in package
```java
package org.example.project.assertions;
import java.util.Objects;
import org.assertj.core.api.AbstractAssert;
import org.assertj.core.api.SoftAssertions;

public class MyProjectSoftAssertions extends SoftAssertions {

  public static class MyProjectClass {
    private final Object value;
    public MyProjectClass(Object value) {
      this.value = value;
    }

    public Object getValue() {
      return value;
    }
  }

  public static class MyProjectClassAssert extends AbstractAssert<MyProjectClassAssert, MyProjectClass> {

    public MyProjectClassAssert(MyProjectClass actual) {
      super(actual, MyProjectClassAssert.class);
    }

    public MyProjectClassAssert hasValue(Object value) {
      if (!Objects.equals(actual.getValue(), value)) {
        failWithMessage("Expecting value to be <%s> but was <%s>:", value, actual.getValue());
      }
      return this;
    }
  }

  public MyProjectClassAssert assertThat(MyProjectClass actual) {
    return proxy(MyProjectClassAssert.class, MyProjectClass.class, actual);
  }
}
```

The following test code
```java
 @Test
  public void assertValue() {
    MyProjectSoftAssertions softly = new MyProjectSoftAssertions();
    softly.assertThat(new MyProjectClass("v2")).hasValue("v1");
    softly.assertAll();
  }
```
produces the following error message:
```
org.assertj.core.api.SoftAssertionError: 
The following assertion failed:
1) Expecting value to be <v1> but was <v2>:
at MyProjectSoftAssertions$MyProjectClassAssert$ByteBuddy$nP0a48xo$auxiliary$OKW4UxOl.call(MyProjectSoftAssertions$MyProjectClassAssert$ByteBuddy$nP0a48xo$auxiliary$OKW4UxOl.java:-1)
```
